node.text:
Old school games that don’t involve any technology are not only a lot of fun, but they actually provide our kids with so much important sensory and strengthening opportunities that will roll over into school based skills. 

While summer may be closing in, the fun doesn’t have to disappear-enjoy some family game nights with some of these suggestions ☝️.

Start with fatter crayons and as fine motor skills and dexterity improve, scale down to the traditional crayon width. 🖍

node.text:
Young children want to be independent, but independence with dressing takes time.  It’s a complex activity that relies on adequate 

⭐️strength
⭐️fine motor coordination
⭐️body awareness
⭐️sequencing
⭐️bilateral integration
... and so much more!

The key is exposure.  Even if your child is not able to dress himself yet, let him attempt to be part of the process as much as possible. 

Repeated attempts and opportunities to problem solve will help him move closer to independence with this skill. 

Here is a super GENERAL breakdown of dressing ability and it’s important to remember that every child will progress at his or her own pace. How much is your little one able to do? Let us know in the comments! 👇

node.text:
Initial jumping typically begins around age 2, but then there’s so much more!!!

In order to begin jumping, a toddler needs strong calf, hip and core muscles. 

Lots of squatting and standing, walking on tip toes, and climbing can help get these muscles ready. 

If your child can’t seem to get off the ground initially, try bouncing on a soft, springy surface like a bed or couch to help the child feel the motion.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Tots On Target on August 15, 2021. May be an image of one or more people and text that says 'Sometimes we have to release the idea of how we thought it would go, and just justletitbe w .totsontarget.com'.

node.text:
There were many things I thought I’d NEVER do as a mom and there were many scenarios that I thought would play out in very specific ways. 
.
But truthfully, they never worked out quite like I planned. 
.
When I finally accepted that the messy and disappointing days were ok too, I found more peace with my parenting. 
.
Even on the hard days... you’re doing a great job ❤️

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Tots On Target on August 14, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Grasp www.totsontarget.com Development Digital Supinate (1-2 years old) Digital Pronate Grasp (2-3yersld) (2-3 years Quadrupod Grasp (4-5 years old) Tripod Grasp (5-6 years old)'.

node.text:
As children grow, their hands develop more strength and dexterity, which allows them to eventually hold a pencil with a tripod grasp (first 3 fingers). ✏️ 🤚 
.
Hanging from monkey bars, crawling through obstacle courses, squishing and modeling play dough, and snipping with scissors are all good play activities that help refine and develop those little hand muscles.
.
If your child is still displaying an immature grasp pattern for his/her age, reach out to a pediatric OT for more guidance. 👍

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Tots On Target on August 13, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'WAYS TO DEVELOP A PROPER PENCIL GRASP in preschool 1. Painting and coloring on an easel 2. Playing with play dough Hanging from monkey bars, climbing trees, swinging on swings TOTs TARGET'.

node.text:
⭐️ Holding and writing with a pencil is hard!  It takes skillful control and lots of strength and endurance of all the small muscles in the hand. 

⭐️And the best way to develop these muscles is through PLAY!  Many everyday preschool activities help to  build up the strength and dexterity of those hands and fingers! 

⭐️So keep the days filled with play.  So when kindergarten rolls around in September, those little hands will be ready!

node.text:
Crossing Midline helps children build strong connections between the right and left sides of their brains so they can easily accomplish tasks and activities like crawling reciprocally, getting dressed, playing sports, reading, writing, and scanning a room. 

In the first few months, babies are already starting to cross midline visually, then when reaching for toys and rolling. 

Here are a few ways for you to challenge your baby with some crossing midline activities. 

Keep in mind that by giving your baby lots of floor time for tummy time, rolling, crawling etc. your baby will likely find crossing midline opportunities on his or her own so you don’t need to “work” on this skill-just incorporate lots of play and movement into your baby’s every day.
